In this proclamation, President Barack Obama declares February 2014 as National Teen Dating Violence Awareness and Prevention Month. He highlights the alarming statistics of teen dating violence, stating that 1 in 10 American teenagers experience physical violence in their relationships. The president emphasizes the long-lasting effects of dating violence, such as substance abuse, depression, and poor academic performance. He calls for a commitment to preventing abuse, supporting survivors, holding offenders accountable, and building a culture of respect. The president encourages everyone to learn the risk factors and warning signs of dating violence. He provides resources for those in abusive relationships, including the National Dating Abuse Helpline. The president mentions his administration's dedication to preventing dating violence and raising awareness among teens and their families. He references the White House Task Force to Protect Students from Sexual Assault and Vice President Joe Biden's 1 is 2 Many initiative as efforts to combat dating violence. The president calls on all Americans to support efforts in their communities and schools, as well as in their own families, to empower young people to develop healthy relationships and prevent and respond to teen dating violence.